Global system settings, containing preferences that always apply identically to all defined users.
Secure system settings, containing system preferences that apps can read but are not allowed to write, unless the device is rooted and the Superuser permission is installed.
System settings, containing miscellaneous system preferences.

System: Control whether the accelerometer will be used to change screen orientation. If 0, it will not be used unless explicitly requested by the application; if 1, it will be used by default unless explicitly disabled by the application.
Secure: Whether display color inversion is enabled. If 0, no. If 1, yes.
Secure: Whether accessibility is enabled (1) or diabled (0).
Global: Whether Airplane Mode is on.
Global: A comma separated list of radios (bluetooth, cell, nfc, wifi, wimax) that need to be disabled when airplane mode is on.
System: Persistent store for the system-wide default alarm alert.
Secure: Setting to allow mock locations and location provider status to be injected into the LocationManager service for testing purposes during application development.
Secure: Origins for which browsers should allow geolocation by default. The value is a space-separated list of origins.
Global: If 1, the activity manager will aggressively finish activities and processes as soon as they are no longer needed. If 0, the normal extended lifetime is used.
Secure: A 64-bit number (as a hex string) that is randomly generated when the user first sets up the device and should remain constant for the lifetime of the user’s device.

Global: Scaling factor for Animator-based animations. This affects both the start delay and duration of all such animations. Setting to 0 will cause animations to end immediately. The default value is 1.
System: Auto caps in text editors. If 0, no. If 1, yes.
System: Auto punctuate in text editors. This feature converts two spaces to a “.” and space. If 0, no. If 1, yes.
System: Auto replace (AutoText) in text editors. If 0, no. If 1, yes.
Global: Prefer the date, time and time zone to be automatically fetched from the network (NITZ). If 0, no. If 1, yes.
Global: Prefers the time zone to be automatically fetched from the network (NITZ). If 0, no. If 1, yes.
Secure: Whether background data usage is allowed. If 0, no. If 1, yes.

System: Determines whether remote devices may discover and/or connect to this device. If 0, neither connectable nor discoverable. If 1, connectable but not discoverable. If 2, discoverable and connectable.

System: Bluetooth discoverability timeout. If this value is non-zero, then Bluetooth becomes discoverable for a certain number of seconds, after which is becomes simply connectable. The value is in seconds.
Global: Whether bluetooth is enabled (1) or disabled (0).
Global: Whether data roaming is enabled (1) or disabled (0).
System: Date format string; mm/dd/yyyy, dd/mm/yyyy or yyyy/mm/dd.
Global: Name of an application package to be debugged.
Secure: The input method used by default, holding the ID of the desired method.
Global: Whether user has enabled development settings.
Global: Whether the device has been provisioned. If 0, no. If 1, yes.
System: Whether or not to dim the screen. If 0, no. If 1, yes.
System: Whether the audible DTMF tones are played by the dialer when dialing. If 0, no. If 1, yes.
System: CDMA only settings DTMF tone type played by the dialer when dialing. If 0, normal. If 1, long.
Secure: List of the enabled accessibility providers.
Secure: List of input methods that are currently enabled. This is a string containing the IDs of all enabled input methods, each ID separated by ':'.

System: What happens when the user presses the end call button when in call. If 0, do nothing. If 1, go to the home screen. If 2, put the device to sleep and locks the keyguard. If 3, go to the home screen or puts the device to sleep if the user is already on the home screen.
System: Whether the haptic feedback (long presses, etc.) are enabled. If 0, no. If 1, yes.
Global: Host name and port for global http proxy. Uses ':' seperator for between host and port.
Secure: The visibility of input method selector. If 0, invisible. If 1, visible.

Global: Whether the package installer should allow installation of apps downloaded from sources other than Google Play. If 1, allow installing from other sources. If 0, only allow installing from Google Play.

Secure: The degree of location access enabled by the user. If 0, Location access disabled. If 1, Network Location Provider disabled, but GPS and other sensors enabled. If 2, Reduced power usage, such as limiting the number of GPS updates per hour. If 3, Best-effort location computation allowed.
Secure: Comma-separated list of location providers that activities may access.
Secure: Whether autolock is enabled (1) or disabled (0).
Secure: Whether lock pattern will vibrate as user enters. If 0, no. If 1, yes.
Secure: Whether lock pattern is visible as user enters. If 0, no. If 1, yes.
System: Determines which streams are affected by ringer mode changes. The stream type’s bit should be set to 1 if it should be muted when going into an inaudible ringer mode.
System: Determines which streams are affected by mute. The stream type’s bit should be set to 1 if it should be muted when a mute request is received.
Global: Preference for which network(s) should be used. Only the connectivity service should touch this.
System: A formatted string of the next alarm that is set, or the empty string if there is no alarm set.
System: Persistent store for the system-wide default notification sound.
System: Persistent store for the system-wide default ringtone URI.
System: Control whether to enable automatic brightness mode. If 0, use manually set level. If 1, automatic adjustment.
System: The screen backlight brightness between 0 and 255.
System: The timeout before the screen turns off.
Secure: Setting to record the input method subtype used by default, holding the ID of the desired method.
Secure: Settings classname to launch when Settings is clicked from All Applications.
System: Whether the setup wizard has been run before (on first boot), or if it still needs to be run. If non-zero, has been run in the past. If 0, has not been run.
System: Showing password characters in text editors. If 0, no. If 1, yes.
Global: Control whether the process CPU usage meter should be shown. If 0, no. If 1, yes.
System: Whether the sounds effects (key clicks, lid open, etc) are enabled.
Secure: Whether accessibility is enabled (1) or diabled (0).

Global: Whether we keep the device on while the device is plugged in. If 0, never stay on while plugged in. If 1, stay on for AC charger. If 2, stay on for USB charger. If 4, to stay on for wireless charger.
System: Display times as 12 or 24 hours. If 12, 12-hour format. If 24, 24-hour format.
Secure: If touch exploration is enabled (1) or disabled (0).
Global: Scaling factor for activity transition animations. If 0, disable window animations.
Secure: Default text-to-speech engine speech rate. 100 = 1x.
Secure: Space delimited list of plugin packages that are enabled.

Global: If 1, when launching “Debug app” it will wait for the debugger before starting user code. If 0, it will run normally.

Global: The maximum number of times we will retry a connection to an access point for which we have failed in acquiring an IP address from DHCP. A value of N means that we will make N+1 connection attempts in all.
Global: Maximum amount of time in milliseconds to hold a wake-lock while waiting for mobile data connectivity to be established after a disconnect from Wi-Fi.
Wi-Fi mobile data transition wakelock timeout
Global: Whether to notify the user of open networks.
Global: Delay (in seconds) before repeating the Wi-Fi networks available notification. Connecting to a network will reset the timer.
Global: When the number of open networks exceeds this number, the least-recently-used excess networks will be removed.
Wi-Fi number of open networks kept
Global: Whether the Wi-Fi should be on. Only the Wi-Fi service should touch this.

Global: The policy for deciding when Wi-Fi should go to sleep (which will in turn switch to using the mobile data as an Internet connection). If 0, default. If 1, use defaul when the device is on battery but never go to sleep when the device is plugged in. If 2, never go to sleep.
System: If using static IP, the primary DNS’s IP address.
System: If using static IP, the secondary DNS’s IP address.
System: If using static IP, the gateway’s IP address.
System: If using static IP, the net mask.
System: Whether to use static IP and other static network attributes. If 0, no. If 1, yes.
Global: Whether the Wi-Fi watchdog is enabled. If 0, no. If 1, yes.
Global: Scaling factor for normal window animations. If 0, disable window animations.
